<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-219-868  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 219 868.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 9 1990 n1381* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Open Software Foundation is fraying at the edges.andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Toshiba America Inc. (membership).andO;Product:   OSF-l (Operating system) (product development).andO;Topic:     Open Software FoundationMembership ListResignationConsortiaProduct Delay.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>OPEN SOFTWARE FOUNDATION IS FRAYING AT THE EDGESandM;In the last few months, eight members of the Open Software Foundation havefailed to renew their membership in the organisation.andP;  The only oneapparently anxious to trumpet its defection, however, is Toshiba America,which continues to retain its membership in the rival Unix Internationalorganisation.andP;  Toshiba vice-president Don Anderson said the firm allowed itsmembership to lapse because it failed to see any advantage in continuing topay its $25,000 subscription fee.andP;  &quot;OSF's only argument to continuingmembership is being part of the Request for Technology process.andP;  But member'sdon't have any influence.andP;  The OSF staff make all the decisions anyway - andblatantly say so.andP;  And if a company wants to influence the process it can doso without being a member&quot;.andP;  Toshiba, which has opted to use SunMicrosystems' Sparc processor, was one of the companies endorsing Unix SystemV.4 at its roll-out by Unix International in New York in October.andP;  TheFoundation, which now claims 185 members, declined to name the firms thathave dropped out, quoting a &quot;management decision&quot; to protect theiridentities.andP;  An spokeswoman indicated that erstwhile members Apollo andLachman Associates, both recently acquired, were in addition to the eightdefectors.andP;  Hewlett-Packard, she noted, nobly continues to honour Apollo'smajor $4.5m a year commitment as a founder member.andP;  But the delays in gettingOSF/1 out the door are straining the organisation, which has cancelled plansfor a distributed database Request For Tech nology, and with members havingto invest in their own Unix developments to stay competitive in the meantime,the Foundation is in danger of further cuts.andO;</TEXT></DOC>